Questo che vedete √® quello che resta del progetto ‚ÄúBuran‚Äù: il programma spaziale sovietico che puntava a costruire space shuttle riutilizzabili.

Come si pu√≤ notare, il progetto era basato su piani trafugati della NASA, e rimase attivo dal 1974 al 1993, ma solo uno dei prototipi riusc√¨ ad arrivare in orbita, nel 1988.

Dopo il crollo dell'URSS il programma √® stato messo in stand-by e gli space shuttle incompiuti sono stati abbandonati. Uno di questi √® andato distrutto nel 2002, quando l'hangar che lo ospitava √® crollato durante una tempesta, mentre un altro prototipo si trova in un museo in Germania. I due shuttle rimasti al cosmodromo di Baikonur, in Kazakistan, sono probabilmente gli ultimi che restano.

Le foto che vedete sono state scattate in grande segreto, infatti la base √® tuttora sorvegliata ed il fotografo che ha scattato queste foto √® anonimo. Pochissime persone sono riuscite a entrare a Baikonur e a uscirne senza problemi, e lui √® uno di loro.

Voyager 1 and 2 employed a clever maneuver known as the slingshot effect or gravity assist to maximize their speed and reach their destination efficiently. 

This technique relies on the gravitational pull of a planet to propel the spacecraft forward. As Voyager approached a planet, such as Jupiter or Saturn, it used the planet‚Äôs gravity to alter its trajectory, gaining momentum in the process. By carefully aligning the spacecraft‚Äôs trajectory with the planet‚Äôs gravitational field, engineers strategically planned these encounters to boost the spacecraft‚Äôs velocity. 

This gravity assist enabled the Voyagers to conserve fuel, shorten their travel time, and explore multiple celestial bodies during their epic interplanetary journeys. Thanks to this innovative technique, Voyager 1 and Voyager 2 have ventured far beyond our solar system, providing us with valuable insights about the outer realms of space.

üåå We have been to Mars! (Almost)
We did not actually walk on the Red Planet, but our research and development unit manager, @alebalo88 flew to Hawaii to participate in an analogue programme organized by @hi_seas_missions

What does that mean? In a nutshell, an Analog is a simulation of a space mission in which participants are asked to behave exactly as they would on a spaceship or an extraterrestrial planet.

The aim of these intiatives is to test critical technologies for the development of the human spaceflight and to to study in depth the difficult environment of a space flight. People have to deal with unforeseen events, quick decisions with a lack of information, cooperation, living for 24 hours in an uncomfortable space, and psychological challenges.

In addition, Alessandro took a test for the Faculty of Psychology at the University of Turin during his experience.

With the development of the New Space Economy, space tourism will become a reality, and here at Argotec we have already been working on human spaceflight technology for years.

A new era of adventures in space is ahead of us. And experiences like Alessandro's will be extremely helpful in charting the course.
